OpenShift S2I Customization Lab

In this lab, you become familiar with using OpenShift’s s2i utility to layer your application onto an existing OpenShift builder image. This lab also demonstrates the creation of a custom S2I builder image based on Apache HTTPD. After creating the Apache HTTPD builder image, you make it available on OpenShift through an image stream and a custom template, which allows for quick creation of new static web applications.

Goal

  • Use s2i utility to create a Docker image

  • Create a custom builder S2I image

  • Create a custom OpenShift template

Prerequisites

  • OpenShift’s oc command-line client installed on the client workstation and authenticated with the remote OpenShift master API

  • Git client installed on the client workstation

  • Docker installed on the client workstation

  • make utility installed on the client workstation

  • Maven

  • Go language installed on the client workstation (https://golang.org/)

  • GitHub account, to host the application code used in the S2I build (https://github.com)

  • Docker Hub account, to host the S2I Docker image (https://hub.docker.com)

1. Download S2I Utility

You may skip this section if you are using the ocplab VM, which is preconfigured with the s2i utility, or if you set up your local machine as described in the first lab of the course, because that setup also includes the s2i utility.

  1. Download the latest s2i binary for your platform from https://github.com/openshift/source-to-image/releases/latest.

  2. Unzip the downloaded file and place the s2i binary into a directory in your $PATH.

  3. Test the s2i utility:

    $ s2i version
s2i v1.1.6

2. Create Java Container Using S2I

OpenShift provides S2I-enabled Java images for building and running Java applications. The Java S2I builder image assembles your application source with any required dependencies to create a new image containing your Java application. This resulting image can be run by either OpenShift or Docker. This Java builder image is intended for use with Maven-based Java standalone projects, which are run using the main class.

In this section of the lab, a simple "Hello World" Java application is layered onto the OpenShift Java builder image and executed on your client workstation.

  1. Become root (we are running this whole lab as root)

    $ sudo -i

  2. Create the hellos2i Maven-based project:

    $ cd $HOME
$ mvn archetype:generate -DarchetypeGroupId=org.apache.maven.archetypes -DarchetypeArtifactId=maven-archetype-quickstart -DgroupId=org.acme -DartifactId=hellos2i -Dversion=1.0

  3. Press the Enter key when prompted for the package name.

2.1. Test Maven Project (Optional)

  1. Change to the directory with the newly created hellos2i Java project:

    $ cd $HOME/hellos2i

  2. Build and package the Maven project:

    $ mvn clean package

  3. Run the hellows2i application:

    $ java -cp target/hellos2i-1.0.jar org.acme.App
Hello World!

2.2. Create Docker Image with OpenShift’s S2I

In this section, you create a Docker image using OpenShift’s S2I build workflow.

  1. Set the environment variables used during build and runtime:

    $ cd $HOME/hellos2i
$ mkdir .s2i
$ echo -en "AB_JOLOKIA_OFF=true\nJAVA_MAIN_CLASS=org.acme.App" > .s2i/environment

  2. Create the image:

    $ docker pull fabric8/s2i-java
$ s2i build . fabric8/s2i-java java-s2i-helloworld

    • This command pulls down the fabric8/s2i-java builder image from Docker Hub. Using the source code of your hellos2i Java application, the s2i utility then builds the application and layers it onto the Java builder image. From this, a target application image named java-s2i-helloworld is created and pushed to your Docker registry.

  3. Verify that the new target image exists in your Docker registry:

    $ docker images | grep java-s2i-helloworld
java-s2i-helloworld    latest    54a664c3fe63    477.2 MB

  4. Run the java-s2i-helloworld application:

    $ docker run java-s2i-helloworld
Starting the Java application using /opt/run-java/run-java.sh ...
exec java -cp .:/deployments/* org.acme.App
Hello World!

You have successfully containerized a standalone Java application using OpenShift’s s2i utility and a Java builder image.

3. Create Custom S2I Image

S2I is OpenShift’s framework to build Docker images starting from source code and a builder image. The result is a new image that runs the assembled application. OpenShift comes with a number of S2I images for various languages, such as Ruby, Perl, and PHP, and for frameworks such as Node.js and Java EE. Custom S2I images can be built for use cases where out-of-the-box S2I images cannot be used.

In this lab, you build a simple S2I builder image for static websites served by Apache HTTPD.

Custom S2I images can be built from scratch, typically starting from a base Docker image for Red Hat Enterprise Linux or CentOS. In addition, the s2i OpenShift utility is used to create, build, and test new images. The tool is written in Go, and requires Go and Docker to be installed.

3.1. Build Base S2I Image

  1. Create an output directory named $HOME/httpd-s2i:

    $ cd $HOME
$ mkdir $HOME/httpd-s2i

  2. Build a skeleton S2I image definition and change to the output directory:

    $ s2i create httpd-s2i $HOME/httpd-s2i
$ cd $HOME/httpd-s2i

    • The output directory, $HOME/httpd-s2i, is now populated with the following:

      • Dockerfile

      • Makefile

      • A test directory

      • A hidden .s2i directory

3.2. Customize S2I Image

  1. Replace the contents of the generated Dockerfile with the following:

    FROM openshift/base-centos7

EXPOSE 8080

# Install Apache httpd from www.softwarecollections.org
RUN yum install -y \
  https://www.softwarecollections.org/repos/rhscl/httpd24/epel-7-x86_64/noarch/rhscl-httpd24-epel-7-x86_64-1-2.noarch.rpm && \
    yum install -y --setopt=tsflags=nodocs httpd24 && \
    yum clean all -y

LABEL io.k8s.description="Platform for building and running httpd applications" \
      io.k8s.display-name="Apache 2.4" \
      io.openshift.expose-services="8080:http" \
      io.openshift.tags="builder,httpd" \
      # this label tells s2i where to find its mandatory scripts
      # (run, assemble, save-artifacts)
      io.openshift.s2i.script-url="image:///usr/libexec/s2i"

# Copy the S2I scripts from the specific language image to /usr/libexec/s2i (where we set the label above)
COPY ./s2i/bin/* /usr/libexec/s2i/

# Each language image can have 'contrib' a directory with extra files needed to
# run and build the applications.
COPY ./contrib/ /opt/app-root

# In order to drop the root user, we have to make some directories world
# writeable as OpenShift default security model is to run the container under
# random UID.
RUN sed -i -f /opt/app-root/etc/httpdconf.sed /opt/rh/httpd24/root/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf && \
    head -n151 /opt/rh/httpd24/root/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf | tail -n1 | grep "AllowOverride All" || exit && \
    chmod -R a+rwx /opt/rh/httpd24/root/var/run/httpd && \
    chown -R 1001:1001 /opt/app-root

USER 1001

# Set the default CMD to print the usage of the language image
CMD ["usage"]

    • Note the use of openshift/base-centos7 as the base image.

    • Note the use of Apache HTTPD from Software Collections at https://www.softwarecollections.org. Software Collections allows for the installation and use of multiple versions of software on the same system without affecting system-wide installed packages.

    • Docker containers on OpenShift are not run as root, so configuration is required to start and run HTTPD as a non-root user.

  2. Create a contrib/etc directory at the project root, and change to this directory:

    $ mkdir -p $HOME/httpd-s2i/contrib/etc
$ cd $HOME/httpd-s2i/contrib/etc

  3. Create a file named scl_enable in the $HOME/httpd-s2i/contrib/etc directory with this content:

    # IMPORTANT: Do not add more content to this file unless you know what you are
#            doing. This file is sourced every time the shell session is opened.
#
# This will make scl collection binaries work out of box.
unset BASH_ENV PROMPT_COMMAND ENV
source scl_source enable httpd24

  4. Create a file named httpdconf.sed in the $HOME/httpd-s2i/contrib/etc directory with this content:

    s/^Listen 80/Listen 0.0.0.0:8080/
s/^User apache/User default/
s/^Group apache/Group root/
s%^DocumentRoot "/opt/rh/httpd24/root/var/www/html"%DocumentRoot "/opt/app-root/src"%
s%^<Directory "/opt/rh/httpd24/root/var/www/html"%<Directory "/opt/app-root/src"%
s%^<Directory "/opt/rh/httpd24/root/var/html"%<Directory "/opt/app-root/src"%
s%^ErrorLog "logs/error_log"%ErrorLog "/tmp/error_log"%
s%CustomLog "logs/access_log"%CustomLog "/tmp/access_log"%
151s%AllowOverride None%AllowOverride All%

    • This file contains a number of sed commands used to configure the HTTPD server. It is used in the RUN command in the Dockerfile.

    • Configuration specifics include:

      • The HTTPD server listens to port 8080, and is bound to all interfaces (0.0.0.0).

      • The HTTPD server is run as default:root, the default application user created in the openshift/base-centos7 image.

      • The root document for the HTTPD server is set to /opt/app-root/src, the HOME directory defined in the openshift/base-centos7 image.

  5. Change the working directory to the .s2i/bin directory:

    $ cd $HOME/httpd-s2i/s2i/bin

  6. Review the files that drive the assembly and runtime behavior of the S2I image in this directory: assemble, run, usage, and save-artifacts.

  7. Edit the run file so that its content looks like this:

    #!/bin/bash -e
#
# S2I run script for the 'httpd-sti' image.
# The run script executes the server that runs your application.
#
# For more information see the documentation:
#	https://github.com/openshift/source-to-image/blob/master/docs/builder_image.md
#

exec httpd -D FOREGROUND

  8. Make sure the run script is executable:

    $ chmod +x $HOME/httpd-s2i/s2i/bin/run

    • Leave the other files in the directory unchanged.

3.3. Build S2I Image and Push to DockerHub

In this section, you build the Docker image, test it, and push it to your DockerHub account.

  1. Change your directory to the root folder of the S2I project, and invoke the make command to build the Docker image:

    $ cd $HOME/httpd-s2i
$ make

    • The Makefile delegates to the Docker API and builds an image with the name httpd-s2i.

  2. Verify the existence of the new Docker image:

    $ docker images | grep httpd-s2i
httpd-s2i                                            latest              4fedbbc1f463        4 minutes ago       396.8 MB

  3. To test the image, modify the test application in the test/test-app directory of the S2I project.

    • Because the purpose of the S2I image is to serve static HTTP files, the test application can be as simple as a static HTML file.

  4. Modify the test/test-app/index.html file shown here:

    <html>
  <head>
    <title>HTML Home Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>This is the home page</h1>
  </body>
</html>

  5. Perform an S2I build with the httpd-s2i image and the test application:

    $ cd $HOME/httpd-s2i
$ s2i build test/test-app/ httpd-s2i:latest httpd-s2i-test

---> Installing application source...
---> Building application from source...

  6. Verify that the result is a new Docker image, httpd-s2i-test:

    $ docker images | grep httpd-s2i
httpd-s2i-test                                       latest              cdfd77e66d64        2 minutes ago       396.8 MB
httpd-s2i                                            latest              4fedbbc1f463        26 minutes ago      396.8 MB

  7. Run the httpd-s2i-test Docker image in the background, forwarding the container’s 8080 port to the host’s 8080 port:

    $ docker run -p 8080:8080 -d --name httpd-s2i-test httpd-s2i-test
512cf9673f111e38fd7723ea8406241e59982ffff0e1af6db3f48deb564d2a06
    Docker returns the id of the container that is now running. This id will be different in your environment.

  8. Verify that your application is working:

    $ curl http://localhost:8080
<html>
  <head>
    <title>HTML Home Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>This is the home page</h1>
  </body>
</html>

  9. Now that we have verified that our container works stop and remove the container:

    $ docker rm -f httpd-s2i-test

  10. Push the httpd-s2i image to DockerHub to make the image available to the OpenShift environment, replacing <DockerHub user name> with your DockerHub user name:

    $ docker tag httpd-s2i docker.io/<DockerHub user name>/httpd-s2i:2.4
$ docker login
Login with your Docker ID to push and pull images from Docker Hub. If you don't have a Docker ID, head over to https://hub.docker.com to create one.
Username: <Dockerhub user name>
Password:
Login Succeeded
$ docker push docker.io/<DockerHub user name>/httpd-s2i:2.4
    On RHEL Linux systems you need to use docker.io as a prefix for the image for the push command because the default registry points to the Red Hat Registry. On other systems you can omit the docker.io prefix.

4. Deploy Application Using Custom S2I Builder Image

In this section, you define an image stream for the builder image. This is necessary to deploy the application on OpenShift using the new custom S2I builder image. You also create a Git source repository as a starting point for the build.

4.1. Create Image Stream

  1. On the machine where your OpenShift client is installed, create a httpd-s2i-imagestream.yaml file with contents similar to the following file, replacing the three instances of ${DockerHub user name} with your DockerHub user name:

    apiVersion: v1
kind: ImageStream
metadata:
  name: httpd-s2i
  annotations:
    openshift.io/display-name: httpd-s2i
spec:
  tags:
  - name: "2.4"
    annotations:
      openshift.io/display-name: "httpd 2.4"
      description: Build and run static web apps served by httpd 2.4
      iconClass: icon-apache
      tags: builder,httpd
      supports: httpd,httpd:2.4
      version: "2.4"
    from:
      kind: DockerImage
      name: docker.io/${DockerHub user name}/httpd-s2i:2.4
  - name: "latest"
status:
  dockerImageRepository: docker.io/${DockerHub user name}/httpd-s2i
  tags:
  - tag: "2.4"
    items:
    - dockerImageReference: docker.io/${DockerHub user name}/httpd-s2i:latest

    • This file defines an image stream for your S2I image, including metadata, such as version and tags.

  2. Create the image stream on OpenShift, using the oc OpenShift client:

    $ oc create -f httpd-s2i-imagestream.yaml

  3. Verify that the image stream is successfully created by doing either of the following:

    • Use the oc OpenShift client to enter the following:

      $ oc get is
NAME                    DOCKER REPO                                            TAGS             UPDATED
httpd-s2i               172.30.41.165:5000/wkocpappdev/httpd-s2i               2.4              4 minutes ago

    • Use the OpenShift console as shown here:

4.2. Create Source Code Project

To deploy an application built with the HTTPD S2I image, you need a source code project on a public Git hosting site, such as GitHub. The purpose of the S2I image is to serve static HTTP files. The source code application needs an index.html in the project root.

  1. Create a new repository in your GitHub account.

  2. On your client machine, create a folder for the source files.

  3. Change directories to the folder:

    $ mkdir -p $HOME/s2i-project
$ cd $HOME/s2i-project

  4. Create an index.html file, which acts as the home page of the static website with the following content:

    <html>
  <head>
    <title>HTML Home Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>This is the home page in OpenShift</h1>
  </body>
</html>

  5. Initialize your project folder as a Git repository:

    $ git init

  6. Add the GitHub clone URL of the GitHub repository:

    $ git remote add origin <GitHub clone URL>

  7. Add and commit the index.html file to the Git repository:

    $ git add index.html
$ git commit -m "Home page"

  8. Push to the remote repository on GitHub (you will be prompted for your GitHub credentials):

    $ git push origin master

4.3. Build Application Using OpenShift Command Line

To build and deploy the static website on OpenShift, you can use the oc CLI or the OpenShift web console. In this section, you build the application using the CLI.

  1. On the machine where your OpenShift client is installed, issue the following command, replacing <GitHub repository URL> with the URL of the source repository on GitHub:

    $ oc new-app httpd-s2i:2.4~<GitHub repository URL> --strategy=source --name=httpd-test

4.4. Build Application Using OpenShift Web Console

To build the application through the OpenShift web console:

  1. Log in to the OpenShift web console.

  2. Click the project link to enter your project.

  3. At the top, click Add To project.

  4. In the Filter by name or description field enter httpd as the search term:

  5. Click Select under your builder image.

  6. Enter httpd-console-test for Name and the URL of your GitHub repository for Git Repository URL, then click Create:

    • The next page shows a success message with some details on how to manage the application:

  7. Click Continue to overview to go back to your dashboard.

  8. Monitor the progress of the build and deployment through the OpenShift web console:

  9. After a successful build and deployment, navigate to the URL exposed by the route to test the application.

4.5. Explore Application Life Cycle

The BuildConfig created as part of the deployment is configured with different triggers that control the circumstances in which it is run and when a new build is triggered. The following example illustrates this:

$ oc get bc/httpd-test -o yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: BuildConfig
metadata:
  annotations:
    openshift.io/generated-by: OpenShiftNewApp
  creationTimestamp: 2017-03-14T20:31:58Z
  labels:
    app: httpd-test
  name: httpd-test
  namespace: wkocpappdev
  resourceVersion: "131455"
  selfLink: /oapi/v1/namespaces/wkocpappdev/buildconfigs/httpd-test
  uid: 45d20622-08f5-11e7-bf54-0632724841dc
spec:
  nodeSelector: null
  output:
    to:
      kind: ImageStreamTag
      name: httpd-test:latest
  postCommit: {}
  resources: {}
  runPolicy: Serial
  source:
    git:
      uri: https://github.com/wkulhanek/httpd-s2i.git
    type: Git
  strategy:
    sourceStrategy:
      from:
        kind: ImageStreamTag
        name: httpd-s2i:2.4
        namespace: wkocpappdev
    type: Source
  triggers:
  - github:
      secret: rUo_3N5q2LMzb7FuJDCK
    type: GitHub
  - generic:
      secret: _EtXUL5wWLrB8joN5gcE
    type: Generic
  - type: ConfigChange
  - imageChange:
      lastTriggeredImageID: docker.io/wkulhanek/httpd-s2i@sha256:8eb5c579d53d7e6a5254be47edc4a488b7adb037bfa9b3f22d6e07631eaac34f
    type: ImageChange
status:
  lastVersion: 1

  • The GitHub and Generic triggers allow you to initiate a new build by sending a request to the OpenShift API endpoint.

  • A typical use case is to configure a GitHub webhook for the push event that calls the OpenShift GitHub webhook URL, to initiate a new build every time new code is pushed to the GitHub repository.

4.6. Set Up GitHub Webhook

Setting up a GitHub webhook is beyond the scope of this lab, but in this section you mimic the process by calling the OpenShift generic webhook URL directly using curl.

  1. Make some change to your source code project, commit, and push to the GitHub repository.

  2. Obtain the generic webhook URL:

    $ oc describe bc/httpd-test
Name:		httpd-test
Namespace:	wkocpappdev

Annotations:	openshift.io/generated-by=OpenShiftNewApp

From Image:	ImageStreamTag wkocpappdev/httpd-s2i:2.4
Output to:	ImageStreamTag httpd-test:latest

Build Run Policy:	Serial
Triggered by:		Config, ImageChange
Webhook GitHub:

5. Deploy Application Using Custom Template

In OpenShift, a template describes a set of objects that can be parameterized and processed to produce a list of objects for OpenShift to create. These objects include services, build configurations, and deployment configurations.

In this section, you create a template for the S2I build, and use this template to quickly create new applications based on the HTTPD S2I image.

  1. On the machine where your OpenShift client is installed, create a file named httpd-s2i-template.json with this content:

    {
    "kind": "Template",
    "apiVersion": "v1",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "httpd-s2i",
        "creationTimestamp": null,
        "annotations": {
            "description": "This is an example of a static web application on OpenShift",
            "tags": "instant-app,httpd"
        }
    },
    "labels": {
        "template": "httpd-s2i"
    },
    "objects": [
        {
            "kind": "Service",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "metadata": {
                "annotations": {
                    "description": "The web server's http port."
                },
                "labels": {
                    "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                "creationTimestamp": null
            },
            "spec": {
                "ports": [
                    {
                        "port": 8080,
                        "targetPort": 8080
                    }
                ],
                "selector": {
                    "deploymentConfig": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                }
            }
        },
        {
            "kind": "Route",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "id": "${APPLICATION_NAME}-http-route",
            "metadata": {
                "annotations": {
                    "description": "Route for application's http service."
                },
                "labels": {
                    "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}-http-route"
            },
            "spec": {
                "host": "${APPLICATION_HOSTNAME}-<YOUR PROJECT NAME>.apps.<YOUR DOMAIN>",
                "to": {
                    "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                    "kind": "Service"
                }
            }
        },
        {
            "kind": "ImageStream",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "metadata": {
                "labels": {
                    "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
            }
        },
        {
            "kind": "ImageStream",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "metadata": {
                "name": "httpd",
                "creationTimestamp": null
            },
            "spec": {
                "dockerImageRepository": "docker.io/<YOUR DOCKERHUB ID>/httpd-s2i"
            },
            "status": {
                "dockerImageRepository": ""
            }
        },
        {
            "kind": "BuildConfig",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "metadata": {
                "labels": {
                    "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "creationTimestamp": null,
                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
            },
            "spec": {
                "triggers": [
                    {
                        "github": {
                            "secret": "${GITHUB_TRIGGER_SECRET}"
                        },
                        "type": "github"
                    },
                    {
                        "generic": {
                            "secret": "${GENERIC_TRIGGER_SECRET}"
                        },
                        "type": "generic"
                    },
                    {
                        "imageChange": {},
                        "type": "imageChange"
                    }
                ],
                "source": {
                    "git": {
                        "ref": "${GIT_REF}",
                        "uri": "${GIT_URI}"
                    },
                    "type": "Git"
                },
                "strategy": {
                    "type": "Source",
                    "sourceStrategy": {
                        "from": {
                            "kind": "ImageStreamTag",
                            "name": "httpd-s2i:2.4",
                            "namespace": "<YOUR NAMESPACE>"
                        }
                    }
                },
               "output": {
                    "to": {
                        "kind": "ImageStreamTag",
                        "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}:latest"
                    }
                },
                "env": []
             }
        },
        {
            "kind": "DeploymentConfig",
            "apiVersion": "v1",
            "metadata": {
                "labels": {
                    "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                "creationTimestamp": null
            },
            "spec": {
                "replicas": 1,
                "selector": {
                    "deploymentConfig": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                },
                "strategy": {
                    "type": "Recreate"
                },
                "triggers": [
                    {
                        "type": "ImageChange",
                        "imageChangeParams": {
                            "automatic": true,
                            "containerNames": [
                                "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                            ],
                            "from": {
                                "kind": "ImageStream",
                                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                            }
                        }
                    }
                ],
                "template": {
                    "metadata": {
                        "labels": {
                            "application": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                            "deploymentConfig": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                        },
                        "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}"
                    },
                    "spec": {
                        "containers": [
                            {
                                "env": [],
                                "image": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                                "imagePullPolicy": "Always",
                                "name": "${APPLICATION_NAME}",
                                "ports": [
                                    {
                                        "containerPort": 8080
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    ],
    "parameters": [
        {
            "name": "APPLICATION_NAME",
            "description": "Application NAME"
        },
        {
            "name": "GIT_URI",
            "description": "GIT URI"
        },
        {
            "name": "GIT_REF",
            "description": "Git branch"
        },
        {
            "name": "GIT_CONTEXT_DIR",
            "description": "Path within Git project to build; empty for root project directory."
        },
        {
            "name": "GITHUB_TRIGGER_SECRET",
            "description": "Github trigger secret",
            "generate": "expression",
            "from": "[a-zA-Z0-9]{8}"
        },
        {
            "name": "GENERIC_TRIGGER_SECRET",
            "description": "Generic build trigger secret",
            "generate": "expression",
            "from": "[a-zA-Z0-9]{8}"
        },
        {
            "name": "APPLICATION_HOSTNAME",
            "description": "Application hostname"
        }
    ]
}

  2. Review the different sections of the template:

    • This template creates ImageStream, BuildConfig, DeploymentConfig, Service, and Route objects based on the HTTPD S2I image.

    • This template also specifies parameters, the values for which are either provided in the template or generated automatically based on patterns specified in the template (such as for GITHUB_TRIGGER_SECRET and GENERIC_TRIGGER_SECRET).

  3. Before uploading the template to OpenShift, make these changes so that it works in your environment:

    1. On line 55, replace <YOUR PROJECT NAME>.apps.<YOUR DOMAIN> with a suitable URL for your environment.

    2. On line 80, replace the value of the dockerImageRepository option with the S2I image name in your DockerHub account.

    3. On line 128, replace the value of the namespace option with the name of your OpenShift project.

  4. Create the template on OpenShift:

    $ oc create -f httpd-s2i-template.json
template "httpd-s2i" created

  5. Verify that the template appears in the list of templates in the OpenShift console:

    1. On your project’s overview page, click Add To Project.

    2. Enter httpd in the field Filter by name or description:

  6. Create an application with the template:

    1. Click Select in the box for the httpd-s2i template on the right.

    2. On the next page, click Edit parameters and fill in suitable values for the template parameters:

    3. Scroll down and click Create.

      • This creates all the objects configured in the template and initiates a build.

  7. Click Continue to overview to return to your project.

  8. As with the exercises above, use the console or the client CLI to monitor the build’s progress and review the different objects that are created. Note that it may take a few seconds for the build to be kicked off.

  9. Once the build is finished, test your application in a browser.

6. Clean up

When you are finished, delete the OpenShift applications:

oc delete template httpd-s2i
oc delete is httpd-s2i
oc delete all -lapp=httpd-test
oc delete all -lapp=httpd-console-test
oc delete all -lapp=httpd-s2i
